: false, "mention": "dihydrotestosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996193647384644, "span": {"begin": 548, "end": 567}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013196"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DHT", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9998108148574829, "span": {"begin": 569, "end": 572}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 603, "end": 605}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000728"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "androgen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994950294494629, "span": {"begin": 690, "end": 698}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "androgen receptor", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9771968722343445, "span": {"begin": 690, "end": 707}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 788, "end": 790}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 855, "end": 857}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 915, "end": 917}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1063, "end": 1065}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6715"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "5&alpha;-reductase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9952301979064941, "span": {"begin": 1078, "end": 1096}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013739"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "testosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9960213303565979, "span": {"begin": 1129, "end": 1141}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013196"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DHT", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9988020658493042, "span": {"begin": 1145, "end": 1148}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000728"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "androgen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.997056245803833, "span": {"begin": 1164, "end": 1172}}], "text": "This non-adjacent KER describes a fetal decrease in androgen receptor (AR) activation in the genital tubercle causing hypospadias in male offspring, postnatally. During fetal development, androgens induce differentiation of the bipotential genital tubercle to a penis, including closure of the urethra. Androgens signal through AR and reduced fetal AR activation can therefore disrupt penis differentiation and lead to the genital malformation hypospadias. Reduced AR activation may happen both through reduced ligand availability (testosterone or dihydrotestosterone (DHT)) and by direct antagonism of AR (Amato et al., 2022; Mattiske &amp; Pask, 2021).   The upstream KE &lsquo;decrease, androgen receptor activation&rsquo; (KE 1614) refers to the in vivo event of overall reduction in AR activation. In this case, it therefore refers to a reduction in AR activation in the genital tubercle. Currently, decreased AR activation in mammals is only directly measured in vitro and not in vivo. Instead, indirect assessment of this KE may come from assays measuring AR antagonism, 5&alpha;-reductase activity (the enzyme converting testosterone to DHT), or decreased androgen levels (Draskau et al., 2024).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:56:45 +0000 2026"}